<!-- ============ FAQ ============ -->
<section class="section" style="padding-bottom: 80px;">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-header">
      <div class="section-eyebrow">Frequently Asked Questions</div>
      <h2 class="section-title">Everything you need to know.</h2>
    </div>
    <div style="max-width: 800px; margin: 0 auto;">
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
          What makes Teamwork Commerce OMS different from standalone order management systems?
          <span class="faq-icon"><i class="ti ti-plus"></i></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Teamwork's OMS is natively integrated with POS, Inventory, RFID, and 121 Commerce AI — not bolted on through middleware. This means order routing decisions are based on RFID-verified real-time stock (99.9% accuracy), not stale batch-synced data. The AI routing engine evaluates shipping cost, store labor, proximity, tax impact, stock depth, and carbon footprint simultaneously to optimize every fulfillment decision for margin, not just speed.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
          How does the AI routing engine decide where to fulfill an order?
          <span class="faq-icon"><i class="ti ti-plus"></i></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>The Order Fill Logic scores every available fulfillment node across thousands of variables per second — including shipping rates, store labor availability, regional tax implications, stock depth (to avoid selling last units), customer proximity, and even carbon footprint. Each node receives a score, and the AI selects the optimal one. It can also intelligently split orders across multiple nodes when that produces a better outcome.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
          Can Teamwork Commerce OMS handle ship-from-store and BOPIS?
          <span class="faq-icon"><i class="ti ti-plus"></i></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. Ship-from-store turns every retail location into a fulfillment node with AI-generated pick-and-pack tasks for store associates. BOPIS (Buy Online Pick Up In Store) is backed by RFID-verified stock — eliminating the 60% failure rate that plagues retailers relying on barcode-based inventory. Curbside pickup and Buy Online Return In Store (BORIS) are also natively supported.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
          How does Teamwork Commerce OMS compare to New Black EVA and NewStore?
          <span class="faq-icon"><i class="ti ti-plus"></i></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>New Black EVA offers scoring-based order orchestration but requires third-party middleware for RFID and lacks a native AI agent. NewStore focuses heavily on fulfillment but doesn't offer native RFID or merchandising intelligence. Teamwork Commerce uniquely combines AI-powered Order Fill Logic, the industry's only native end-to-end RFID stack (ensuring routing decisions are based on 99.9% accurate inventory), and 30+ years of retail expertise — all in one system with no middleware required.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="faq-item">
        <button class="faq-question" onclick="this.parentElement.classList.toggle('open')">
          Does the OMS support multi-currency and multi-entity operations?
          <span class="faq-icon"><i class="ti ti-plus"></i></span>
        </button>
        <div class="faq-answer"><p>Yes. The OMS operates across multiple legal entities, currencies, and tax jurisdictions. A US-based HQ can manage global operations while regional teams see dashboards in their local currency and language. Automated VAT, GST, and sales tax calculations ensure cross-border fulfillment is always compliant.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

